How do acoustic features of songs influence their rank?¶

Authors: Yashas Lokesh, Renee Yang, Kavya Dagli

Musicologist Dr. Alison Pawley and psychologist Dr. Daniel Mullensiefen out at the University of London claim that it is possible to identify if a song will be popular. Two of the attributes that they predict make songs popular are "longer and detailed musical phrases" and "a higher number of pitches." We will put this claim to the test by analyzing the relationship between song audio features and song rank. We will also explore if there are additional features that influence popularity.

1.2 Dataset Source¶

The database we used consists of two tables:

  1. Contains all Billboard 200 albums from 1963 to the beginning of 2019. Each row contains its position in that week, album name, artist name, and track lengths.
  2. This table contains track names, Spotify IDs, and EchoNest data for tracks from each of the albums above.

The dataset comes from here.

The 'EchoNest' data we mentioned above consists of several factors, and we'll explain what each of them even mean:

  • Acousticness
  • etc. etc.

1.4 Cleaning and Modifying Data¶

After viewing the data, it is apparent that many of the features contain null values. We decided to drop these values to prevent complications with performing operations on the two dataframes later on.

We'll also drop the columns that provide no info to us. We'll be looking at how audio features can influence Billboard 200 rankings, so we don't need the Spotify IDs.

In [7]:
# drop null values in both tables
acoutstic_features = acoustic_features.dropna()
albums = albums.dropna()

acoustic_features.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
albums.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

acoustic_features.drop(labels=['id', 'album_id'], inplace=True, axis=1)

Now we can get the highest rank for each album. We can do this easily with the df.sort_values() and df.groupby() methods.

Note: The date value that we get after performing these steps is the date that particular album reached its top position.

Now we'll create a function that will allow us to combine data from the two dataframes. The rank value from the albums DF will be added to acoustic_features. This function should take in an album name from acoustic_features and return the rating.

What if any of the album names don't match up between the two DataFrames? When we first created the function, we assumed that albums would have the same name in both DataFrames. A quick search for the artist 'Ed Sheeran' shows that this isn't true.

In [12]:
print('From Albums:', albums.loc[albums['artist'] == 'Ed Sheeran']['album'].unique())
print('From Acoustic Features:', acoustic_features.loc[acoustic_features['artist'] == 'Ed Sheeran']['album'].unique())

From Albums: ['+' '5' "Don't (EP)" 'x']
From Acoustic Features: ['5' "Don't (EP)" 'x' ' (Divide)']

Given this mismatch in album naming, we decided we'll discard the albums that do not transfer over nicely. Adding these albums would be tedious, manual work and would take time away from our analysis. We'll do this by returning np.nan if the album names did not match up

In [13]:
# stands for 'acoustic_features_rank'
def af_rank(album):
    temp = albums.loc[albums['album'] == album]
    try:
        return temp.values[0][4]
    except:
        return np.nan
In [14]:
acoustic_features['rank'] = acoustic_features['album'].apply(lambda row: af_rank(row))

4.2 Audio Features vs. Rank by Decade¶

Since there was little correlation between rank and audio features, we decided to go ahead and try slitting the songs up by decade to see if this affected results. To see if time has an affect on correlation between audio features and rank, we will create a heat map for 10 different time periods. In order to do this, we can convert the date column from the string type to the DateTime object type. We then create bins by using pandas' date_range function and create the bin column using pandas' cut function.

5. Linear Regression¶

5.1 Null Hypothesis¶

Our null hypothesis states that none of the acoustic features will influence rank.

In the next step, we will verify the null hypothesis.

5.2. Regression with OLS¶

Regression will allow us to determine the strength of the relationship between the rank (our dependent variable) and the audio features (our independent variable).

To begin our regression we will create two separate dataframe for our independent and dependent variables. Our independent variables will reside in the features dataframe and our dependent variables will reside in the target dataframe.

We're using OLS because we can specify a relationship between two values easily by creating an R-like formula.

We'll create relationships between variables that had a correlation coefficient with high magnitude, and keep the others as they are, independent. We're defining a "high magnitude" as those values > 0.5 or < -0.5.

In [39]:
formula = "rank ~ acousticness * energy + \
                  acousticness * loudness + \
                  danceability * valence + \
                  energy * loudness + \
                  duration_ms + \
                  instrumentalness + \
                  key + \
                  liveness + \
                  mode + \
                  speechiness + \
                  tempo + \
                  time_signature + \
                  norm_year"

The * characters indicate that we include both of the arguments as well as another coefficient for the relationship between them.

Next we'll split the dataframe into training and testing subsets. We'll use 80% of the DF for training, the other 20% for testing.

In [40]:
train_data = acoustic_features.sample(frac=0.9, random_state=481)
test_data = acoustic_features.drop(train_data.index)
In [41]:
regres = ols(formula, data=train_data).fit()
regres.summary()

We'll use the regression to predict rank values now. The RegressionResults.predict() method returns a Series of ranks with the associated indices, so we'll combine them in another DataFrame and then use that DF to create a scatter-plot with our predictions on the x-axis and actual rankings on the y-axis. We predicted that acoustic features were not a good indication of rank, so we should expect a graph with points not lined up.

If the prediction was correct, we should expect a diagonal line going from the bottom-left to the top-right.

7. Conclusions¶

7.1 Key Takeaways¶

Based on the heatmap of the correlations of the audio features and the regression analysis of the audio features vs. rank, we can deduce that each of the individual audio features are not strongly correlated to rank, and together they still do not affect the rank of a song. Out of the individual features, it seems that instrumentalness has the highest correlation to rank. This is interesting because it would make Musicologist Dr. Alison Pawley and psychologist Dr. Daniel Mullensiefen's prediction that "longer and detailed musical phrases" make a song more popular more correct as the higher the instrumentalness, the more longer and detailed musical phrases there are. However there did not seem to be evidence that "a higher number of pitches", or speechiness, was individually correlated to rank.

Our regression showed us that acoustic features alone are not a good indication of whether an album will be popular, i.e. if it will reach the top of the Billboard 200. We were already observing that the acoustic features did not correspond strongly to the rank of the song. To make up for this, we added variables in the regression to create relationships between strongly-correlated features. This did not help in the regression, as we got a R-squared coefficient of 0.037.

Since we know that acoustic features alone are not a good indicator of performance on the Billboard 200, this begs the question: what are the factors? Or even, how many factors are there? Some further questions that could be explored are:

  • Has the artist created several successful albums before?
  • How similar are a popular artists' albums' acoustic features?
  • How does the political climate affect the popularity of albums?
  • How did news events surrounding artists contribute to their Billboard performance?
  • How does the tone/message of the song affect its popularity? (This would be an interesting NLP component to add on).
